The architects have understood that the offices also need nursery
The administrative building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
Nobody would say that it hides a small nursery with all the necessary to such facilities also in its interior: walls of colors, creative furnitures and even a park in miniature in the exterior terrace.
Since October of the last year, the children of the employees of Arch.Design can go to it.
The company of architectonic projects Arch.Design, from whose study numerous known buildings of Brno came out, thought from the first sketches of the building Avriopoint about including a space for its mininursery.
In the company they work about 90 people, mainly in the age of the boom baby and wanted to allow the work the architects and draftsmen being able soon to return after the maternity.
Together with the possibility to enjoy a reduced schedule, the nursery is one of the profits that Arch.Design to its workers offers within the framework of its social program.
The builders and architects in this way have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with the care of the children.
The mininursery was an idea about the employees of Arch.Designu themselves and, with the support of the address, they managed to obtain financing of the European Union and of the Ministry of Work and Social Matters.
The mininursery of the company is financed through the European Social Background within the framework of the operative Program of human resources and employment, as well as of the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the financing granted (an endowment of more than 2,8 million Czech crowns) they could buy the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified staff and services.
When it uses the financing (two years) up, the company Arch.Design has the duty to maintain the mininursery in functioning with its own backgrounds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted a year and in the presentation of the application for financing it contributed the company Economy Rating.
The attention of the children is in the hands of qualified staff; besides, a nurse and a professor of the Ministry of Education are present all the day for its cares. The nursery at present receives unlimited children of age, although most of them has less than three years.
Since it is a "mininursery," so alone can receive simultaneously to a maximum of five children, although with the turns they go more during the day.
The functioning of the nursery is flexible to adapt to the needs for the fathers and the children of all the workers have the same law to using the nursery, independently of the hierarchy in the company.
Although they are a teaching and individual cares, the contents of the program of the mininursery are comparable to the program of the usual continuative education.
In it the children not alone play, but they also receive a teaching of quality: from the basic learning up to the preparation for the school, they show up to English.
The class not alone has of toys and table games, but also of a computer for the children.
The presence of small children in the company itself to create a friendly and positive atmosphere.
The fathers can go to see its children in any moment and avoid the stress of collecting late the children of the school when it is far from its working place.
Thus, the fathers are more productive while they work.
It is not surprising that this generates a relation of loyalty between the worker and its employer in a natural way.
This way, Arch.Design is situated among the companies sign that they offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, all in all, this program reinforced the marketing of staff.
The home of the bones keeps being fascinated after 100 years. Observe the interiors of Gaudí
The roof seems the loin of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs remember the column of a dinosaur and the balconies seem the open mouth of a fish.
Like this it is the Home Batlló, in Barcelona, of the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Due to its form similar to a skeleton, the sites nicknamed it "the home of the bones."
Its organic forms, its showy colors, the new use of the stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a façade that remembers to the scales and the omnipresent softly curved lines, all that is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The cover of the home plays with oneiric lines, delicate colors and textures taken out of the nature and out of the fauna.
Paying more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought order, is observed.
At night, all the façade of the home still seems more impressive, since it is illuminated so that the brightness of the colors is improved.
It winds and the torsion of the forms keeps surprising us also in its interior.
The wavy wood copies the frames of the windows, the banisters, the ornaments of the doors, the spy holes and the signs.
The Home Batlló, which he finds in the neighborhood of Eixample at number 43 of the animated commercial street of Passeig de Grácia, rose up from the remodelling of a home of 1877 of the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the home was completed in 1906.
The investor, the rich industrialist Josep Batlló, at first insisted on bringing down the previous building and starting of zero, but he soon accepted the idea about Gaudí of carrying out a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, Antoni Gaudí did not design the Home Batlló, formed by different apartments, alone.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in its plans of the project ornaments rose up for the apartment representative of the owner of the estate and the mosaics used in the façade.
In the façade also working other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of the Casa Batlló was the beginning of the successful collaboration of Jujol with Gaudí.
Jujol took part in the construction of the Home Milá and of the park Güell de Gaudí, in which they find other parts of it.
Due to its organic form, the sites little after its ending nicknamed it "the home of the bones."
Others, due to the mechanism specific to opening of the windows started to call it "the home of the yawns."
It is said also that, at the top of the construction, the sword of San Jorge, boss of Catalonia, appears.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious motifs.
Gaudí projected a unique system for the period of central heating with vents of ventilation and the typical chimneys in the home.
Its dip of forty-five degrees can be strange.
During the construction, Gaudí did not respect the norms of construction of the moment at all and was not let be influential for them.
Still like this, the construction obtained the corresponding license from the beginning, although evidently in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years afterwards, to its ending, the town council was kept so struck with the result that asked that it corrected itself.
The construction including columns even up to the public sidewalk bothered it, for example.
The hotfixes were never carried out, rather on the contrary: so alone fifteen days after the application for the town council, Josep Batlló requested (and it obtained) license for renting the two most upper flats of the building.
In the inferior flats the owner himself installed himself.
In the gallery of the second flat the room was found and in the third flat the bedrooms and the part deprived of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry.
The home, of six flats, is completely crossed by some stairs that it takes up to the terrace of the roof.
The basic elements of the reform consisted in breaking all the angles and direct lines, covering them of curved walls.
Gaudí worked likewise with the modern concept of connection of the space.
The common part can be connected completely opening the doors of the rooms and a bigger group can be communicated in this troublefree way, without the necessary privacy being renounced for more intimate conversations.
The home, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not alone obtained a new façade, but also an unusual roof and two additional flats.
It is impressive likewise how Gaudí plays with the light, white and blue tiles that cover the interior courtyard and skylights.
The game with both colors provides the maximum of light in all the flats of the home.
It was based simply on the beginning of which the white reflex more light that the dark colors, which on the contrary absorb the sunbeams.
Any person can visit the Home Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the list of world patrimony of the humanity of the Unesco.
In the first flat of the home it finds the apartment roomiest and most filled up with the ones accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that it is a very beneficial business and they extended the visits to the common area and to the loft, the terrace of the roof included.
The price of the entry to the monument is not insignificant, reaches the 16,50 euros, although the students, the retired people and the headlines of the touristic cards obtain 20% of discount.
