Climate: the botches of France in its promises of financing
A year after the Agreement of Copenhagen, it is an hour of examining if the promises of financing quickly unblocked (fast start called or precocious) carried out by the developed countries have been respected.
And the French botches have been revealed.
In the Agreement of Copenhagen, the developed countries committed themselves to providing 30.000 million dollars among 2010 and 2012.
The European Union committed to providing 7.200 million euros in three years and France 1.260 millions of euros (that is, 420 million per year).
During the opening of the COP16, the EU has put its best cards on the table to convince its members that its appointment with the financings fast start is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a great complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The noticeable result transparency operation and was noticed for what really it is valid: the developing countries and the civil society would want for all the developed countries to make what was same and with the same level of accuracy.
The EU announces that she has released 2010 2.200 million euros, which situates it in the good path towards the fulfillment of its appointment of 7.200 million in 2012.
But, if we study the situation in a detailed way, the things are more complicated.
According to the Agreement of Copenhagen, the money must be "new and additional" to guarantee that a complementary effort is carried out, without damaging the official help to the development.
Unfortunately, people have not arrived to an agreement on what it means "new and additional."
When the European Commission suggested a harmonization, some Member States, included France, have blocked the procedure.
At present, every cual chooses the reference that it needs more.
For example, the European Commission has taken 2009 for reference: the international financing keeps and 150 million are added in three years in concept of financing fast start.
Other countries have chosen similar references as for the year or at the level of the official help to the development.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of "all the new projects" of 2010 are "new and additional."
In other words, the expenses of the years previous even to the total level of the official help to the development are referred to.
Specifically, the total amount of the help of France to the developing countries can remain stable (or even to decrease), while it pretends that it respects its appointment on the subject of "new and additional" backgrounds...
Another crucial element, the distribution between donations and loans.
Once more, there is not any norm and every cual chooses the method of calculation.
Some, as France, consider that every borrowed euro is equivalent at a donated euro.
Evidently, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans can be justified for specific inversions that are profitable (frequently, related projects with the reduction of broadcasts that are based on more effective technologies), it is fallacious to present a euro that is going to recover as equivalent to a euro that is donated... At the most, only the cost of the loan should be computed for its appointments for the country that grants the loan (that is, the equivalent to an interest rate).
But France does not find such a reasoning useful: he "respects" its appointment of 420 million euros doing 91,5% of loans (389,8 million euros) and 8,5% of donations (36,1 million euros); consult the document of the EU to see it for its own eyes.
It is about the only country of the Union that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it by 46%, whereas Denmark, Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect its appointments with 100% of donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union provides a euro to comply its appointment, France so alone contributes ten cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
A good trick!
In summary, in its financing fast start, France carries out a double abuse: for a part, in relation to the actions in the time and, for another, in relation to the real financial effort.
Using up so alone 36,1 million euros, manages to give the impression that it uses up 420 million "new and additional," as it had been promising.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finances (because it seems that it is Bercy the one who has been occupied of the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, so much in the EU (why were going to keep donating the other Member States when they can simply lend?) as in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not foolish...
The chapter of the precocious financing is a trifle, relatively short-term, in relation to the ensemble of the negotiations on the climate.
